    "body": "### Problem\r\n\r\nOutput from compilers, linters and test utilities generally output errors positions as **`<file>:<line>:<column>` but `<cfile>` only expands the file path, it does not consider line and column.\r\n`gF` can be used to jump to file and line number but it doesn't consider the column.\r\n\r\n\r\n### Expected behavior\r\n\r\nAdd a new spec like <cfile> to expand the path with path and position.\r\nFor instance, consider `<cxfile>` (cursor expanded file) or `<cfilelc>` (cursor file, line and column).\r\n`^` is the position of the cursor\r\n```\r\nundeclared variable at source.c:99:6\r\n                                  ^\r\n```\r\nRunning `:echo expand('<cfilelc>')`  prints `source.c:99:6`.\r\nThen a lua utility can be used to open the file at the position\r\n```lua\r\n  local parts = vim.split(vim.fn.expand('<cfilelc>'), ':')\r\n  local pos_cmd = string.format('call cursor(%s, %s)', parts[2], #parts == 3 and parts[3] or '0')\r\n\r\n  local cmd = string.format('drop %s | %s', parts[1], pos_cmd)\r\n  vim.cmd(cmd)\r\n```\r\nA further enhancement would be changing the behavior of `gF` to consider the column but a major refactor would be needed.\r\n\r\n\r\nI could work on this as it seems fairly simply to do based on the current implementation to handle `<cfile>` (https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/488038580934f301c1528a14548ec0cabd16c2cd/src/nvim/ex_docmd.c#L6979)\r\nbut I'd first like a to get feedback from maintainers and the community.",
